WEBVTT

00:06.673 --> 00:09.718
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

00:09.718 --> 00:14.890
<i>♪ ♪</i>

00:14.890 --> 00:17.476
<i>‐ My name is Levi Arbogast.</i>
<i>I'm from Apple, Idaho.</i>

00:17.476 --> 00:20.145
I'm 43 years old.
I'm a heavy equipment operator.

00:20.145 --> 00:22.940
<i>I started to learn how to make</i>
<i>knives about 20 years ago.</i>

00:22.940 --> 00:25.067
<i>I've never had a problem</i>
<i>with working under pressure.</i>

00:25.067 --> 00:27.152
<i>I spent several years</i>
<i>as a firefighter,</i>

00:27.152 --> 00:29.821
so if you don't like pressure,
then you're kind of screwed.

00:29.821 --> 00:32.491
<i>‐ My name is Chuck Stone.</i>
<i>I'm 62 years old.</i>

00:32.491 --> 00:34.785
I've been blacksmithing
for 35 years.

00:34.785 --> 00:36.787
<i>There's a skill of learning</i>

00:36.787 --> 00:39.039
<i>how to use the hammer</i>
<i>on the anvil,</i>

00:39.039 --> 00:41.375
and I've learned that skill,
and I'm pretty positive

00:41.375 --> 00:43.418
<i>that I'm gonna</i>
<i>be bladesmithing</i>

00:43.418 --> 00:45.837
until I can't
pick the hammer up anymore.

00:45.837 --> 00:48.257
<i>‐ My name is John Phillips.</i>
<i>I'm from Knoxville, Tennessee.</i>

00:48.257 --> 00:50.801
I'm 38 years old.
I'm a full‐time bladesmith.

00:50.801 --> 00:53.637
<i>I mostly make culinary knives</i>
<i>because I love to cook.</i>

00:53.637 --> 00:56.056
I enjoy taking heat
and raw ingredients

00:56.056 --> 00:57.599
and then combining
all that stuff together,

00:57.599 --> 00:59.768
and in the end,
you have a product.

00:59.768 --> 01:02.562
<i>‐ My name is Tommy Rodriguez.</i>
<i>I'm from Dallas, Texas.</i>

01:02.562 --> 01:04.481
I'm 18 years old.
I'm still in high school.

01:04.481 --> 01:06.608
<i>I've been smithing</i>
<i>since I was 13.</i>

01:06.608 --> 01:09.820
<i>My grandfather inspired me</i>
<i>to make knives.</i>

01:09.820 --> 01:12.072
Doug Marcaida is like
an idol to me.

01:12.072 --> 01:13.907
<i>Me and my grandfather,</i>
<i>we used to bond.</i>

01:13.907 --> 01:15.867
And every time he would say,
"It will KEAL," you know,

01:15.867 --> 01:18.829
nothing is more badass
than that.

01:18.829 --> 01:21.707
‐ Bladesmiths,
welcome to The Forge.

01:21.707 --> 01:23.792
You fellas are here to engage
in three timed rounds

01:23.792 --> 01:25.836
of edged weapon‐making
competition specifically

01:25.836 --> 01:28.880
designed to push every aspect
of your capabilities

01:28.880 --> 01:31.300
to the absolute limits
in front of a panel

01:31.300 --> 01:33.969
of expert judges who determines
which of you is our next

01:33.969 --> 01:35.512
"Forged in Fire" champion,

01:35.512 --> 01:39.725
walking out of here
with a check for $10,000.

01:39.725 --> 01:42.936
Up first, two‐time "Forged
in Fire" champion Ben Abbott.

01:42.936 --> 01:45.314
Next, historic weapons
re‐creation specialist

01:45.314 --> 01:46.648
David Baker.

01:46.648 --> 01:50.694
And last, edged weapons
specialist Doug Marcaida.

01:50.694 --> 01:53.238
Gentlemen, they say being
competitive and creative

01:53.238 --> 01:54.948
can bring out the child
in all of us.

01:54.948 --> 01:58.368
Each of you was assigned
an anvil at random.

01:58.368 --> 02:02.456
Now we're gonna unveil
what's underneath those cloths.

02:02.456 --> 02:05.208
Levi, you're first.
Go ahead and drop that cloth.

02:05.208 --> 02:06.626
<i>♪ ♪</i>

02:06.626 --> 02:08.045
‐ Nice.

02:08.045 --> 02:09.671
‐ That's a toy airplane.

02:09.671 --> 02:12.758
‐ I like toys.
I drive a giant Tonka.

02:12.758 --> 02:14.468
It's just a giant toy
for a grown man

02:14.468 --> 02:15.927
who's still wanting
to be a kid.

02:15.927 --> 02:17.054
‐ Chuck, you're next.

02:17.054 --> 02:18.889
<i>♪ ♪</i>

02:18.889 --> 02:19.931
‐ [laughs]

02:19.931 --> 02:21.350
‐ That is a toy robot.

02:21.350 --> 02:22.643
‐ [laughs]

02:22.643 --> 02:24.645
‐ John, you're up next.

02:24.645 --> 02:26.146
‐ [laughs]
‐ All right.

02:26.146 --> 02:27.981
‐ You've got a locomotive.

02:27.981 --> 02:30.609
And then on the end here,
Tommy.

02:30.609 --> 02:32.027
‐ All right, man.

02:32.027 --> 02:34.446
‐ We've got a toy fire truck.

02:34.446 --> 02:35.656
‐ What the [bleep]?

02:35.656 --> 02:37.574
<i>Making a blade</i>
<i>out of a toy fire truck</i>

02:37.574 --> 02:40.452
is the last damn challenge
I would've expected them

02:40.452 --> 02:43.038
<i>to put in front of me.</i>

02:43.038 --> 02:44.623
‐ Gentlemen, in the first round
of competition,

02:44.623 --> 02:47.084
you'll have to harvest
mild steel from these toys

02:47.084 --> 02:50.295
to combine with W1 round stock
to forge a billet

02:50.295 --> 02:51.922
from which you will make
your signature blade

02:51.922 --> 02:54.966
in your signature style.

02:54.966 --> 02:56.259
You'll have three hours
in this round

02:56.259 --> 02:58.011
in which to complete
those blades.

02:58.011 --> 02:59.388
In the second round,
you'll attach handles

02:59.388 --> 03:00.972
to your blades,
turning them into

03:00.972 --> 03:03.517
fully functional weapons that
will be tested for strength

03:03.517 --> 03:06.478
and durability
in a toy truck chop

03:06.478 --> 03:09.481
and for edge retention
in a rope slice.

03:09.481 --> 03:11.608
When the time runs out,
after the judges

03:11.608 --> 03:13.902
have evaluated your work,
one of you will be asked

03:13.902 --> 03:16.571
to surrender your blade
and leave The Forge.

03:16.571 --> 03:20.242
Good luck, bladesmiths.
Your three hours starts now.

03:20.242 --> 03:21.284
<i>[intense music]</i>

03:21.284 --> 03:23.245
‐ Toys, toys, toys.

03:23.245 --> 03:25.789
‐ Mothers across America
are gonna hate

03:25.789 --> 03:28.542
"Forged in Fire" this week,
because your children

03:28.542 --> 03:30.544
are gonna go
rip their toys apart,

03:30.544 --> 03:31.962
looking for mild steel.

03:31.962 --> 03:33.463
[laughter]

03:33.463 --> 03:35.298
‐ Come on.

03:35.298 --> 03:37.008
<i>So I look at this fire truck</i>
<i>and I realize</i>

03:37.008 --> 03:38.760
the only part
that's gonna be usable on it

03:38.760 --> 03:41.471
are the side panels,
so my plan is to take

03:41.471 --> 03:44.015
<i>the fire truck panel,</i>
<i>turn it into a San Mai taco,</i>

03:44.015 --> 03:48.311
<i>and wedge the piece</i>
<i>of my W1 in between it.</i>

03:48.311 --> 03:50.021
‐ I'm a big fan of the San Mai
technique myself.

03:50.021 --> 03:51.231
<i>There are three styles</i>
<i>of San Mai.</i>

03:51.231 --> 03:52.441
<i>There's the taco</i>
<i>where you bend it around</i>

03:52.441 --> 03:53.859
<i>and you inset your steel,</i>

03:53.859 --> 03:56.027
<i>you can grind a groove in</i>
<i>and inset your steel,</i>

03:56.027 --> 03:57.821
<i>or you can just start</i>
<i>with three separate pieces</i>

03:57.821 --> 04:00.907
<i>of steel, tack them together,</i>
<i>and weld them together.</i>

04:00.907 --> 04:04.286
‐ I'm gonna be making
a kind of kukri‐style blade.

04:04.286 --> 04:05.912
I've never made a blade
out of a fire truck,

04:05.912 --> 04:07.664
so let's see how it goes.

04:07.664 --> 04:10.041
‐ Some of these pieces
you can see on the toys

04:10.041 --> 04:11.960
are large pieces;
others are smaller.

04:11.960 --> 04:14.129
So combining that steel
with a W1,

04:14.129 --> 04:16.631
you need enough volume
to make that knife.

04:16.631 --> 04:19.634
<i>‐ As a kid, I spent more time</i>
<i>taking apart toys</i>

04:19.634 --> 04:21.344
<i>than I spent</i>
<i>playing with them.</i>

04:21.344 --> 04:24.639
But I've never tried to make
a knife out of a toy.

04:24.639 --> 04:27.058
<i>There's a piece of steel</i>
<i>on either side of the cabin,</i>

04:27.058 --> 04:31.480
<i>and my plan is to do</i>
<i>a San Mai sandwich method.</i>

04:31.480 --> 04:34.733
Usually before I do a San Mai,
I'll have three pieces of metal

04:34.733 --> 04:36.485
that are all the same size

04:36.485 --> 04:38.528
<i>because you need everything</i>
<i>to heat evenly</i>

04:38.528 --> 04:40.906
all the way through
to get those welds to set.

04:40.906 --> 04:43.992
<i>But here I've got a big piece</i>
<i>of round stock</i>

04:43.992 --> 04:47.412
and then two very thin pieces
of mild steel,

04:47.412 --> 04:51.166
<i>so it's gonna be tricky</i>
<i>to make everything work.</i>

04:51.166 --> 04:54.377
‐ Is it me, or do I see
off‐season Santa out there?

04:54.377 --> 04:55.462
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:55.462 --> 04:56.922
Toys and Chuck's beard.

04:56.922 --> 04:58.256
‐ That's a serious work of art.

04:58.256 --> 04:59.925
‐ Yeah, really.
‐ [laughs]

04:59.925 --> 05:02.594
<i>‐ My plan is to take</i>
<i>the mild steel</i>

05:02.594 --> 05:05.347
<i>and fold it over</i>
<i>into a San Mai taco.</i>

05:05.347 --> 05:07.140
San Mai can make
a real strong blade,

05:07.140 --> 05:09.768
<i>'cause the high carbon steel</i>
<i>you use is sandwiched</i>

05:09.768 --> 05:11.186
<i>in between mild steel,</i>

05:11.186 --> 05:13.563
and the mild steel
has a little flex.

05:13.563 --> 05:16.107
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:16.107 --> 05:17.776
<i>‐ I'm gonna make</i>
<i>a camp chopper,</i>

05:17.776 --> 05:19.861
<i>something with a nice curve</i>
<i>on the blade,</i>

05:19.861 --> 05:21.196
something that's got
a lot of heft.

05:21.196 --> 05:24.491
‐ You want to talk about
a "King Kong" re‐creation,

05:24.491 --> 05:25.742
this is it, man.

05:25.742 --> 05:27.869
Levi just tearing
into this thing.

05:27.869 --> 05:30.205
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:30.205 --> 05:32.833
<i>‐ I'm gonna use the San Mai</i>
<i>method to make my knife.</i>

05:35.544 --> 05:38.046
Make sure I get
a damn good weld.

05:38.046 --> 05:39.840
I got my metal in the forge.

05:39.840 --> 05:41.633
I'm gonna try to flatten
it all out.

05:41.633 --> 05:43.844
I'm gonna try to sand
the two together, weld it up,

05:43.844 --> 05:46.429
I'll have my knife,
and I'll just start shaping it,

05:46.429 --> 05:48.807
get a little edge on there;
I'll be ready to go.

05:48.807 --> 05:50.100
‐ Bladesmiths!

05:50.100 --> 05:51.893
One hour has elapsed.

05:51.893 --> 05:54.604
‐ These guys all seem
to be going with the San Mai.

05:54.604 --> 05:56.940
They have to get those
toy parts totally clean

05:56.940 --> 05:58.775
and then get the steel
to the right temperature

05:58.775 --> 06:00.235
to set a good forge weld.

06:00.235 --> 06:02.070
<i>♪ ♪</i>

06:02.070 --> 06:04.072
<i>‐ I promised my grandfather</i>
<i>before he passed away</i>

06:04.072 --> 06:06.157
that I would compete,
and that's why I'm here today.

06:06.157 --> 06:07.534
<i>If he were still alive,</i>
<i>he'd be like,</i>

06:07.534 --> 06:08.910
"Wow, you even got
on the show."

06:08.910 --> 06:10.245
<i>♪ ♪</i>

06:10.245 --> 06:12.539
This hydraulic press
is awesome,

06:12.539 --> 06:18.169
but I underestimate the power
that it has behind it, and...

06:18.169 --> 06:20.672
‐ What is Tommy doing?

06:20.672 --> 06:22.090
‐ Starts like this...

06:22.090 --> 06:23.466
goes to this...

06:23.466 --> 06:25.260
<i>then goes to that.</i>

06:25.260 --> 06:27.220
I've drawn this billet out
to the point where

06:27.220 --> 06:28.722
it's no longer a kukri,

06:28.722 --> 06:31.057
<i>and it's not</i>
<i>gonna be a kukri.</i>

06:31.057 --> 06:32.309
‐ That thing's a cutlass.

06:32.309 --> 06:33.435
Look at that thing.

06:33.435 --> 06:34.811
<i>‐ I need a new plan.</i>

06:34.811 --> 06:35.896
I'm gonna make it a slicer.

06:35.896 --> 06:38.899
<i>♪ ♪</i>

06:38.899 --> 06:41.693
<i>‐ I want to get the W1 down</i>
<i>to a nice even thickness</i>

06:41.693 --> 06:44.154
so that I can stick
the mild steel on it.

06:44.154 --> 06:45.739
<i>The side of the train</i>
<i>is all painted</i>

06:45.739 --> 06:47.198
<i>with black spray paint,</i>

06:47.198 --> 06:50.118
<i>and the other side</i>
<i>is pretty clean</i>

06:50.118 --> 06:52.621
to weld onto the side
of the W1.

06:52.621 --> 06:55.624
And then, of course...
brain fart.

06:55.624 --> 06:58.668
I welded the wrong side
to the blade.

06:58.668 --> 07:00.920
That paint's gonna cause
delamination.

07:00.920 --> 07:03.465
So know I've gotta
cut that off and redo it.

07:03.465 --> 07:05.133
<i>It's a really silly mistake,</i>

07:05.133 --> 07:06.468
and I'm hoping that it
doesn't cost me too much time.

07:06.468 --> 07:09.596
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:09.596 --> 07:13.391
‐ I have my W1 flat,
and now I have to combine

07:13.391 --> 07:16.353
some of the mild steel
from the robot.

07:16.353 --> 07:19.439
<i>I just need to place it</i>
<i>over the backbone of the knife</i>

07:19.439 --> 07:21.691
<i>where it's gonna have</i>
<i>the most stress</i>

07:21.691 --> 07:22.817
and hope that works.

07:22.817 --> 07:24.778
‐ That's not a bad idea.

07:24.778 --> 07:26.655
The taco technique
adds a lot of strength.

07:26.655 --> 07:29.199
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:29.199 --> 07:32.243
<i>‐ As I'm drawing this W1 out,</i>
<i>my goal is to get it</i>

07:32.243 --> 07:34.871
to the same size
as the airplane wings.

07:34.871 --> 07:36.915
Piece o' cake.

07:36.915 --> 07:40.377
It's time to do my San Mai
and get welding.

07:40.377 --> 07:43.213
I have not done a forge weld
this long before.

07:43.213 --> 07:45.090
<i>The surfaces</i>
<i>have to be perfect,</i>

07:45.090 --> 07:47.258
<i>'cause then there's</i>
<i>14 1/2 inches of weld</i>

07:47.258 --> 07:49.386
that could go wrong
anyplace on it.

07:49.386 --> 07:51.262
Big sparks.

07:51.262 --> 07:55.517
‐ Levi right away throwing
those mighty hammer blows.

07:55.517 --> 07:56.851
<i>‐ I'm a traditional</i>
<i>blacksmith.</i>

07:56.851 --> 07:58.853
<i>I do it all by hand.</i>

07:58.853 --> 08:01.064
And you gotta hit it
with vengeance.

08:01.064 --> 08:03.358
Good weld.

08:03.358 --> 08:05.360
‐ Two hours has elapsed!

08:05.360 --> 08:07.904
‐ I need to forge weld this.

08:07.904 --> 08:11.616
The entire challenge
is based on whether or not

08:11.616 --> 08:14.160
I get this forge weld
set properly.

08:14.160 --> 08:15.620
<i>Heat up my taco,</i>

08:15.620 --> 08:17.330
<i>I'm gonna wedge</i>
<i>that W1 in between it,</i>

08:17.330 --> 08:19.207
<i>I'm gonna cover</i>
<i>that bad boy in flux,</i>

08:19.207 --> 08:21.793
and I'm gonna hit it
till it's stuck.

08:21.793 --> 08:24.462
‐ Tommy is kind of
making me nervous.

08:24.462 --> 08:29.217
He put that folded‐over staple
of steel on a dirty blade,

08:29.217 --> 08:31.010
no MIG welding
to hold it still,

08:31.010 --> 08:34.264
and is just trying
to hammer it together.

08:34.264 --> 08:37.100
It's a really, really difficult
way to make that stick.

08:37.100 --> 08:39.811
<i>‐ I'm grinding off</i>
<i>the excess steel, and boom.</i>

08:39.811 --> 08:42.981
Yeah, that is not welded.

08:42.981 --> 08:44.357
I have to forge weld it again,

08:44.357 --> 08:47.068
so I'm definitely behind
right now.

08:47.068 --> 08:50.113
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:50.113 --> 08:53.283
<i>‐ Now that I've got everything</i>
<i>cleaned up and rewelded,</i>

08:53.283 --> 08:54.409
it's really important for me

08:54.409 --> 08:55.660
to get this metal
really, really hot.

08:55.660 --> 08:57.829
<i>That mild steel</i>
<i>requires a lot more heat</i>

08:57.829 --> 08:59.039
than high carbon steel

08:59.039 --> 09:00.373
in order to get the forget weld
to stick.

09:00.373 --> 09:01.416
‐ There you go.

09:01.416 --> 09:02.876
You really want that steel

09:02.876 --> 09:05.003
up to a hot working temperature
without burning it.

09:05.003 --> 09:07.505
‐ I feel real comfortable
behind the power hammer,

09:07.505 --> 09:09.799
and I'm not a big dude,
so I gotta use

09:09.799 --> 09:13.219
any mechanical advantages
that I got.

09:13.219 --> 09:15.388
‐ John's over there
on the power hammer, man,

09:15.388 --> 09:19.059
and he looks like he's building
a big Khyber‐style knife.

09:19.059 --> 09:20.226
‐ Yeah.

09:20.226 --> 09:21.436
<i>‐ It looks really good.</i>

09:21.436 --> 09:23.313
<i>Everything is a nice</i>
<i>even color.</i>

09:23.313 --> 09:24.481
When I hammer on it,
I'm not hearing

09:24.481 --> 09:27.358
any sort of hollow noises
or anything.

09:27.358 --> 09:30.445
<i>So I feel like everything</i>
<i>is nice and tight.</i>

09:30.445 --> 09:32.072
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:32.072 --> 09:34.157
<i>‐ The forge weld</i>
<i>is going pretty good.</i>

09:34.157 --> 09:35.867
You heat it up,
get it good and hot,

09:35.867 --> 09:38.453
<i>hit it, and repeat.</i>

09:38.453 --> 09:40.872
‐ It's funny that
we have a Chuck here

09:40.872 --> 09:44.042
in the middle of our
child's play competition.

09:44.042 --> 09:47.879
And he's making
a murderous‐looking blade.

09:47.879 --> 09:50.465
<i>[person screams]</i>

09:50.465 --> 09:51.674
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:51.674 --> 09:53.218
<i>‐ After I get a forge weld,</i>

09:53.218 --> 09:55.637
I'm thinking, "I gotta
get this thing shaped."

09:55.637 --> 09:57.263
All right.

09:57.263 --> 09:59.974
If there was any issues
with the weld not being good

09:59.974 --> 10:02.143
or delamming,
it would definitely show up

10:02.143 --> 10:03.603
when I'm doing the grinding.

10:03.603 --> 10:05.605
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:05.605 --> 10:07.023
Whoo‐hoo!

10:07.023 --> 10:08.608
Crank that baby.
Up she goes.

10:08.608 --> 10:10.485
I gotta get one of these.

10:10.485 --> 10:12.153
I see everything's perfect.

10:12.153 --> 10:14.280
<i>I'm over the hump.</i>
<i>My weld is good.</i>

10:14.280 --> 10:16.199
I'm just making it
look pretty now.

10:16.199 --> 10:18.952
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:18.952 --> 10:21.663
‐ You have only 30 minutes
remaining in the round!

10:21.663 --> 10:22.747
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:22.747 --> 10:25.375
<i>‐ So I get my blade</i>
<i>forge welded.</i>

10:25.375 --> 10:26.584
I need to get
this blade quenched,

10:26.584 --> 10:28.128
and I gotta do it now.

10:28.128 --> 10:30.797
‐ Tommy in the quench.
‐ That's a hot quench.

10:30.797 --> 10:32.549
And that's a recipe
for stress fractures

10:32.549 --> 10:33.758
and a brittle blade.

10:33.758 --> 10:35.718
‐ Oh, yeah.

10:35.718 --> 10:37.887
At this point, I feel great.
My knife is hard.

10:37.887 --> 10:40.348
<i>It's time to clean</i>
<i>the metal up.</i>

10:40.348 --> 10:42.058
[bleep].

10:42.058 --> 10:43.726
<i>There is a lateral crack</i>

10:43.726 --> 10:47.355
<i>going down the middle</i>
<i>of my spine.</i>

10:47.355 --> 10:48.648
<i>This is terrible.</i>

10:48.648 --> 10:50.191
[bleep].

10:50.191 --> 10:52.402
‐ If the weld's bad,
a lot of times, a quench

10:52.402 --> 10:53.945
will make that weld pop
or open up.

10:53.945 --> 10:56.072
‐ Right.
‐ I cannot grind this out.

10:56.072 --> 10:57.699
<i>I need to reforge this.</i>

10:57.699 --> 10:59.367
‐ And it looks like
he's really trying

10:59.367 --> 11:03.496
to just make this forge weld
that's not working out stick.

11:03.496 --> 11:05.373
<i>‐ Time is running out.</i>

11:05.373 --> 11:08.835
If I don't get this mild steel
welded on, I'm going home.

11:08.835 --> 11:10.044
‐ I mean, he's shaking
his head.

11:10.044 --> 11:12.088
‐ I mean, he seems nervous.

11:12.088 --> 11:17.844
‐ Not good.

11:17.844 --> 11:19.512
<i>There is a lateral crack</i>

11:19.512 --> 11:22.223
going down the middle
of my spine.

11:22.223 --> 11:23.892
<i>So I reheat my blade,</i>

11:23.892 --> 11:25.518
<i>put some flux on it,</i>

11:25.518 --> 11:28.688
and I try and set those welds
one last time.

11:28.688 --> 11:30.356
‐ He's really trying to just

11:30.356 --> 11:33.401
make this forge weld
that's not working out stick.

11:33.401 --> 11:35.361
‐ At this point,
pull those pieces apart,

11:35.361 --> 11:37.864
clean them, and then
forge weld them together.

11:37.864 --> 11:39.741
It's the only way
he's gonna get it to stick.

11:39.741 --> 11:41.701
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

11:41.701 --> 11:43.244
<i>‐ This is gonna be</i>
<i>the last quench</i>

11:43.244 --> 11:44.787
<i>no matter what happens.</i>

11:44.787 --> 11:47.207
I cannot go back.
I do not have enough time.

11:47.207 --> 11:48.708
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:48.708 --> 11:49.709
‐ Boom.

11:49.709 --> 11:51.044
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:51.044 --> 11:53.546
‐ I look at it,
and the crack's still there.

11:53.546 --> 11:56.049
Not as bad,
but it's still there.

11:56.049 --> 11:57.675
I don't have time
to worry about it,

11:57.675 --> 11:59.010
and I don't have time
to fix it.

11:59.010 --> 12:01.554
<i>I'm gonna start</i>
<i>peeling off material.</i>

12:01.554 --> 12:05.391
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:05.391 --> 12:06.893
‐ John in the quench.

12:06.893 --> 12:08.061
‐ Good.

12:08.061 --> 12:09.979
‐ Whoa!
‐ Whoa!

12:09.979 --> 12:11.314
‐ That's just a testament
to how hot

12:11.314 --> 12:12.565
that must have been
when it went in.

12:12.565 --> 12:14.359
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:14.359 --> 12:17.070
‐ His blades are so hot
going into this oil.

12:17.070 --> 12:18.571
‐ We're seeing
some of these blades

12:18.571 --> 12:19.697
nearly at forge welding
temperature

12:19.697 --> 12:21.115
going into these quenches.

12:21.115 --> 12:22.909
You can literally blow
your San Mai billet apart

12:22.909 --> 12:24.410
if you aren't careful.

12:24.410 --> 12:27.622
<i>‐ I'm really worried</i>
<i>that I got the steel too hot,</i>

12:27.622 --> 12:29.290
because I shouldn't have gotten
two big fireballs

12:29.290 --> 12:30.625
after pulling it out.

12:30.625 --> 12:31.876
<i>If I overheat my blade,</i>

12:31.876 --> 12:33.753
<i>that means that</i>
<i>I'm gonna develop cracks</i>

12:33.753 --> 12:35.255
and possibly have
a brittle blade,

12:35.255 --> 12:38.258
so I'm pretty concerned
about that.

12:38.258 --> 12:39.842
<i>I've got about</i>
<i>ten minutes left,</i>

12:39.842 --> 12:41.928
so I need to get
some of that forge scale off.

12:41.928 --> 12:44.764
[bleep].

12:44.764 --> 12:48.935
I see two big cracks all along
the spine of the blade.

12:48.935 --> 12:51.938
They could be because
I quenched too hot.

12:51.938 --> 12:53.439
<i>There's absolutely nothing</i>
<i>I can do.</i>

12:53.439 --> 12:55.108
<i>This could definitely</i>
<i>send me home.</i>

12:55.108 --> 12:59.153
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:59.153 --> 13:00.697
‐ Chuck just quenched.

13:00.697 --> 13:01.948
‐ I've got a seam here,

13:01.948 --> 13:05.285
but there's enough thick metal
in between there.

13:05.285 --> 13:06.828
Hopefully it'll hold up.

13:06.828 --> 13:09.247
And that little bubble there,
it didn't get welded.

13:09.247 --> 13:11.040
So I'm gonna try
to grind that out.

13:11.040 --> 13:14.294
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:14.294 --> 13:17.046
‐ Levi quenched,
and his blade is very hot.

13:17.046 --> 13:18.673
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:18.673 --> 13:20.550
‐ Flames just start going up
everywhere,

13:20.550 --> 13:22.677
and I instantly thought,
"Oh, I just screwed up."

13:22.677 --> 13:24.804
<i>Way too hot</i>
<i>when I put it in there.</i>

13:24.804 --> 13:26.889
It could delam.
It could split the W1.

13:26.889 --> 13:28.641
<i>There's all sorts of things</i>
<i>that could happen.</i>

13:28.641 --> 13:29.976
<i>I'm gonna pull this thing out,</i>

13:29.976 --> 13:31.644
<i>and it's gonna be</i>
<i>just a disaster.</i>

13:31.644 --> 13:32.687
I don't want to look.

13:32.687 --> 13:33.855
[laughs]

13:33.855 --> 13:37.233
‐ Five, four, three,

13:37.233 --> 13:39.319
two, one.

13:39.319 --> 13:40.611
Bladesmiths,
shut down your machines.

13:40.611 --> 13:41.696
Stop what you're doing.

13:41.696 --> 13:44.991
This first round
of competition is over.

13:44.991 --> 13:46.576
<i>‐ Going into the judging,</i>
<i>I'm worried</i>

13:46.576 --> 13:48.119
<i>that they're gonna think</i>
<i>that those cracks</i>

13:48.119 --> 13:49.704
<i>go deeper than they are</i>

13:49.704 --> 13:51.330
and they're gonna
send me home.

13:51.330 --> 13:53.750
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:53.750 --> 13:55.835
‐ Bladesmiths, in the first
round of competition,

13:55.835 --> 13:59.672
we asked you to take mild steel
from a toy and use it

13:59.672 --> 14:02.508
with some W1 round stock
to make a signature blade

14:02.508 --> 14:03.801
in your signature style.

14:03.801 --> 14:05.011
Now it's time for the judges

14:05.011 --> 14:06.387
to take a closer look
at your work.

14:06.387 --> 14:07.847
Tommy, you're up first.

14:07.847 --> 14:09.932
Please present your blade
to the judges.

14:09.932 --> 14:12.101
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:12.101 --> 14:13.895
<i>‐ Tommy, first off,</i>
<i>I'd pay a lot of attention</i>

14:13.895 --> 14:16.397
to the structure of this steel.

14:16.397 --> 14:18.024
There's some serious
surface cracking.

14:18.024 --> 14:21.277
There's one that's right
up here next to your weld

14:21.277 --> 14:24.155
that goes about halfway
through your blade,

14:24.155 --> 14:26.032
so if you were
to move forward from here,

14:26.032 --> 14:28.201
the structure in this region
is gonna need to be addressed.

14:28.201 --> 14:29.744
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:29.744 --> 14:30.912
‐ All right, John, you're up.

14:30.912 --> 14:32.705
Please present your blade
to the judges.

14:32.705 --> 14:35.249
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:35.249 --> 14:38.419
<i>‐ Right off, it's a good</i>
<i>working chopper shape.</i>

14:38.419 --> 14:39.962
And when you're looking
at one side of your blade,

14:39.962 --> 14:41.589
it's very solid.

14:41.589 --> 14:44.509
But that looks like
a very deep crack.

14:44.509 --> 14:46.094
<i>So if you move</i>
<i>into the second round,</i>

14:46.094 --> 14:48.554
you're gonna need
to come up with a plan

14:48.554 --> 14:49.555
to deal with this.

14:49.555 --> 14:50.598
‐ Mm‐hmm.

14:50.598 --> 14:52.058
‐ All right, Chuck, you're up.

14:52.058 --> 14:54.393
Please present your blade
to the judges.

14:54.393 --> 14:56.479
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:56.479 --> 14:58.272
<i>‐ Obviously you have</i>
<i>your mild steel here</i>

14:58.272 --> 15:00.316
that didn't really
weld properly,

15:00.316 --> 15:01.901
<i>but it's a good thing</i>
<i>that we're not</i>

15:01.901 --> 15:03.945
gonna be
hitting it sideways.

15:03.945 --> 15:06.489
With the edge here,
you have no issues.

15:06.489 --> 15:07.949
It's just that one spot
that you have here,

15:07.949 --> 15:10.326
<i>that stress riser,</i>
<i>could be caused by bending</i>

15:10.326 --> 15:11.577
<i>or overheating the blade.</i>

15:11.577 --> 15:13.579
It could break at this spot,

15:13.579 --> 15:15.957
so you have to deal with that.

15:15.957 --> 15:17.125
‐ All right, Levi, you're up.

15:17.125 --> 15:18.918
Please present your blade
to the judges.

15:18.918 --> 15:25.967
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:27.260 --> 15:31.097
‐ Levi, you quenched
this blade so hot

15:31.097 --> 15:35.518
that you've actually
split the W1 core.

15:35.518 --> 15:37.103
I just don't think
it's repairable.

15:37.103 --> 15:38.938
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:38.938 --> 15:42.108
‐ Levi, unfortunately,
your blade has suffered

15:42.108 --> 15:45.444
critical structural failure
and can no longer continue

15:45.444 --> 15:46.779
in this competition.

15:46.779 --> 15:48.614
I have to ask you
to please leave The Forge.

15:48.614 --> 15:49.991
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:49.991 --> 15:51.784
‐ It's what it is.
[chuckles]

15:51.784 --> 15:53.411
<i>In the end,</i>
<i>I quenched it too hot.</i>

15:53.411 --> 15:55.454
It sucks.
I'm not coming home with a win,

15:55.454 --> 15:56.998
<i>but I came here</i>
<i>for the experience,</i>

15:56.998 --> 15:58.624
<i>and it was a hell</i>
<i>of a journey.</i>

15:58.624 --> 16:00.126
Bring me back
on a redemption or something

16:00.126 --> 16:02.128
so I can go out
and kick some ass again.

16:02.128 --> 16:05.464
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:05.464 --> 16:06.966
‐ Bladesmiths,
congratulations.

16:06.966 --> 16:08.467
You fellas have made it
to the second round

16:08.467 --> 16:10.052
of this competition.

16:10.052 --> 16:12.263
It's time to turn your blades
into fully functional weapons

16:12.263 --> 16:14.807
by attaching handles
and guards to them.

16:14.807 --> 16:17.018
You'll have two hours
in this round to do that

16:17.018 --> 16:18.311
and address the flaws
and issues

16:18.311 --> 16:20.146
that were identified
in your blades.

16:20.146 --> 16:21.939
After the time
runs out on the clock,

16:21.939 --> 16:24.317
we'll be testing your blades
for strength and durability

16:24.317 --> 16:26.527
in a toy truck chop

16:26.527 --> 16:29.155
and for edge retention
in a rope slice.

16:29.155 --> 16:31.824
I remind you that after
your blades have been tested,

16:31.824 --> 16:33.826
one of you will be asked
to surrender your blade

16:33.826 --> 16:35.494
and leave The Forge.

16:35.494 --> 16:37.914
Good luck.
Your two hours starts now.

16:37.914 --> 16:39.165
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:39.165 --> 16:40.166
‐ Welding.

16:40.166 --> 16:41.667
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:41.667 --> 16:43.586
‐ There's a lot of flaws
in these blades.

16:43.586 --> 16:46.047
‐ I expect to see a lot
of welding going on

16:46.047 --> 16:48.299
in these first
couple of minutes.

16:48.299 --> 16:51.177
<i>‐ My game plan for round two</i>
<i>is to weld the spine</i>

16:51.177 --> 16:55.348
and try to get that knife
pulled back together somehow.

16:55.348 --> 16:56.933
<i>If I don't fix this,</i>

16:56.933 --> 16:59.352
it's definitely gonna break
on the first hit.

16:59.352 --> 17:00.728
‐ I think the most
important thing

17:00.728 --> 17:03.356
is to open up that weld channel

17:03.356 --> 17:05.274
so there's something
for the weld to stick to.

17:05.274 --> 17:07.026
If you just squeeze
that closed,

17:07.026 --> 17:08.861
you're just gonna
get a surface weld,

17:08.861 --> 17:10.238
and that cavity, that chamber

17:10.238 --> 17:11.530
inside there's
still gonna be there,

17:11.530 --> 17:13.199
waiting to pop open.

17:13.199 --> 17:16.160
‐ All that heat creates
a really brittle spine,

17:16.160 --> 17:17.620
so now I need
to soften that up.

17:17.620 --> 17:18.996
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:18.996 --> 17:19.997
‐ That is smart.

17:19.997 --> 17:21.415
Give it a nice blue temper

17:21.415 --> 17:23.042
just to remove
any of the brittleness

17:23.042 --> 17:25.086
that comes from just
MIG welding that.

17:25.086 --> 17:27.380
<i>‐ I'm pretty satisfied about</i>
<i>the way things are coming out,</i>

17:27.380 --> 17:30.633
but I have no idea if this
is actually gonna work or not.

17:30.633 --> 17:34.387
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:34.387 --> 17:37.056
‐ Tommy's blade has not only
a pretty significant crack

17:37.056 --> 17:39.725
that runs right at the end
of where he welded on the mild

17:39.725 --> 17:41.477
but also from there forward.

17:41.477 --> 17:42.895
It's like a dry lake bed,
you know?

17:42.895 --> 17:44.063
It's all crackly.

17:44.063 --> 17:46.399
‐ I just start
buffing out material.

17:46.399 --> 17:47.817
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:47.817 --> 17:51.404
As I'm grinding, I realize,
wow, there's another crack

17:51.404 --> 17:52.613
right on the edge.

17:52.613 --> 17:54.865
Oh, [bleep].

17:54.865 --> 17:57.034
[bleep].
[laughs]

17:57.034 --> 17:58.786
<i>If I don't fix</i>
<i>the crack on the edge,</i>

17:58.786 --> 18:00.204
<i>my blade can break,</i>

18:00.204 --> 18:02.748
and I could potentially
not make it to round three.

18:02.748 --> 18:05.459
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:05.459 --> 18:09.505
‐ The first thing I need to do
is get the stress riser fixed.

18:09.505 --> 18:12.592
‐ Where those two staples
of mild steel came together,

18:12.592 --> 18:14.635
there were some real issues
right there.

18:14.635 --> 18:16.762
So I would say
that top half inch

18:16.762 --> 18:18.806
needs to have
some real surgery done,

18:18.806 --> 18:19.932
some grinding and some welding.

18:19.932 --> 18:22.310
‐ That's a lot to do
in two hours.

18:22.310 --> 18:24.270
<i>‐ I'd get fairly good tacks</i>
<i>in there</i>

18:24.270 --> 18:26.939
where I could grind it down,
and it closes most of that up.

18:26.939 --> 18:29.275
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:29.275 --> 18:31.277
Hopefully, it'll hold up.
[chuckles] We'll see.

18:31.277 --> 18:32.987
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:32.987 --> 18:36.949
‐ Well, over here out ahead
of everybody is John.

18:36.949 --> 18:38.075
‐ The knife needs that guard,

18:38.075 --> 18:41.370
so I can get a piece
of Micarta.

18:41.370 --> 18:42.955
<i>I'm hoping that I can work it</i>
<i>a little bit faster</i>

18:42.955 --> 18:45.291
than I could
brass or steel.

18:45.291 --> 18:46.626
Whew.

18:46.626 --> 18:47.960
Now it's time to move on
to the handle.

18:47.960 --> 18:49.670
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:49.670 --> 18:52.298
<i>Take the angle grinder</i>
<i>and cut some notches in</i>

18:52.298 --> 18:55.134
to allow the glue
to grab on to the tang.

18:55.134 --> 18:56.677
‐ Is he weakening the tang?

18:56.677 --> 18:57.970
‐ Yeah, it's very possible

18:57.970 --> 18:59.847
that he's putting stress risers
in the tang.

18:59.847 --> 19:02.808
People assume that
the tang is in a handle block

19:02.808 --> 19:04.644
and it's not moving,
it's a very static thing,

19:04.644 --> 19:07.313
but we've seen
the shock of impact

19:07.313 --> 19:09.231
break handle material,
break the tang.

19:09.231 --> 19:10.650
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:10.650 --> 19:14.987
‐ Bladesmiths, 60 minutes
remaining to finish your work!

19:14.987 --> 19:16.322
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:16.322 --> 19:18.157
<i>‐ Take my handle material</i>
<i>to the drill press,</i>

19:18.157 --> 19:19.492
<i>start drilling some holes.</i>

19:19.492 --> 19:21.661
I picked the cocobolo
because, one,

19:21.661 --> 19:24.330
it's a very hard wood
and it's durable.

19:24.330 --> 19:27.208
Two, it's just pretty, man.

19:27.208 --> 19:29.460
<i>I can't make the hole</i>
<i>in my handle any bigger,</i>

19:29.460 --> 19:31.337
so I have to reduce
the size of my tang.

19:31.337 --> 19:32.838
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:32.838 --> 19:34.882
And I just start
lobbing off material.

19:34.882 --> 19:37.176
[imitates scraping]

19:37.176 --> 19:38.678
‐ That's a long tang.

19:38.678 --> 19:40.179
He doesn't need
all of that length.

19:40.179 --> 19:43.599
‐ I realize there's a big gap.

19:43.599 --> 19:45.142
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:45.142 --> 19:47.019
That's a screwup.

19:47.019 --> 19:49.021
<i>So I'm adding some kind</i>
<i>of turquoise</i>

19:49.021 --> 19:51.857
<i>acrylic‐looking bolster</i>
<i>to my knife.</i>

19:51.857 --> 19:55.069
I mean, it looks cool,
so I mean, that's a plus.

19:55.069 --> 19:58.781
‐ I'm looking at the pantry,
and I see some iron wood there,

19:58.781 --> 20:00.116
and I say,
"Okay, I'm gonna use this

20:00.116 --> 20:01.575
'cause it's a good,
strong wood."

20:01.575 --> 20:03.869
[drill squeaking]

20:03.869 --> 20:06.414
It is giving me
a little bit of a fit.

20:06.414 --> 20:08.207
The wood's getting stuck
in the drill bit,

20:08.207 --> 20:10.209
and my drill bit's not working.

20:10.209 --> 20:12.044
‐ Oftentimes
when the drill bit gets hot

20:12.044 --> 20:13.546
with the stabilized wood,

20:13.546 --> 20:15.631
the material cooks
onto the drill bit.

20:15.631 --> 20:19.218
‐ Quite a few times,
I have to stop the drill

20:19.218 --> 20:21.679
and get it all out
and then start it back again.

20:21.679 --> 20:23.222
Shoot.

20:23.222 --> 20:25.099
I'm so focused on getting
this stuff drilled out,

20:25.099 --> 20:26.809
I'm losing track of time.

20:26.809 --> 20:29.228
‐ I'm worried about him.
I'm worried about Chuck a lot.

20:29.228 --> 20:30.896
‐ This is the point
in the competition where

20:30.896 --> 20:32.481
time management
becomes really important.

20:32.481 --> 20:34.734
<i>‐ I'm feeling</i>
<i>the stress right now.</i>

20:34.734 --> 20:35.901
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:35.901 --> 20:37.069
<i>‐ Cutting the bevel</i>
<i>onto the blade</i>

20:37.069 --> 20:38.154
and it's going great,

20:38.154 --> 20:40.239
except a crack
keeps on popping up.

20:40.239 --> 20:41.657
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:41.657 --> 20:43.284
Welding.

20:43.284 --> 20:45.453
‐ He must've spied
a little crack in his blade.

20:45.453 --> 20:48.247
‐ I think he ground
through his weld.

20:48.247 --> 20:50.833
You have to be careful not
to grind through those welds.

20:50.833 --> 20:54.920
The weld itself is what's
holding things together now.

20:54.920 --> 20:56.088
‐ Feel like a little boy
putting his fingers

20:56.088 --> 20:58.924
in the dam, and there's
water coming out,

20:58.924 --> 21:00.968
and I'm plugging one hole
and...

21:00.968 --> 21:02.261
Welding.

21:02.261 --> 21:03.596
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:03.596 --> 21:05.264
Plug in another hole,
and as soon as I do that,

21:05.264 --> 21:06.390
another one pops up.

21:06.390 --> 21:08.434
Welding again.

21:08.434 --> 21:11.604
I'm getting really frustrated
because no matter what I do,

21:11.604 --> 21:13.355
that crack keeps coming back.

21:13.355 --> 21:15.107
Welding.

21:15.107 --> 21:16.400
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:16.400 --> 21:18.778
‐ 30 minutes, bladesmiths!

21:18.778 --> 21:20.946
Tommy is going
for a Micarta guard.

21:20.946 --> 21:22.448
‐ It's a smart move.

21:22.448 --> 21:25.618
‐ It grinds well.
It shapes well. It glues well.

21:25.618 --> 21:27.453
It's a great handle material.

21:27.453 --> 21:29.330
<i>‐ I gotta make sure</i>
<i>everything is tight,</i>

21:29.330 --> 21:31.582
or my epoxy won't get
a proper hold

21:31.582 --> 21:33.959
and my handle
will come apart in testing.

21:33.959 --> 21:36.670
<i>So I'm making the stack</i>
<i>on top of my knife handle</i>

21:36.670 --> 21:38.714
to compress it down.

21:38.714 --> 21:41.467
‐ Tommy took a piece of steel

21:41.467 --> 21:43.469
and put it
on top of his handle.

21:43.469 --> 21:45.179
‐ There you go.
Put your epoxy up there.

21:45.179 --> 21:46.597
[laughter]

21:46.597 --> 21:47.640
‐ It's the Jenga clamp.

21:47.640 --> 21:49.308
‐ [laughs]

21:49.308 --> 21:51.727
‐ No one walk past it too fast.
I don't want it to fall.

21:51.727 --> 21:53.896
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:53.896 --> 21:55.815
‐ Ten minutes, bladesmiths!

21:55.815 --> 21:57.233
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:57.233 --> 21:58.859
‐ I've still
gotta fit my guard,

21:58.859 --> 22:00.611
I've gotta get
my handle fit on there,

22:00.611 --> 22:03.489
and I really start getting
into panic mode.

22:03.489 --> 22:04.698
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:04.698 --> 22:08.327
When you rush, though,
you mess up even worse.

22:08.327 --> 22:10.538
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:10.538 --> 22:11.622
God dang it.

22:11.622 --> 22:13.082
‐ Chuck just cut himself.

22:13.082 --> 22:16.085
‐ I look down at my hand,
and there's blood‐‐

22:16.085 --> 22:17.419
a lot of blood.

22:17.419 --> 22:18.629
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:18.629 --> 22:20.840
‐ Oh, [bleep].

22:20.840 --> 22:24.218
‐ You can see just how badly
Chuck has cut himself.

22:24.218 --> 22:28.639
‐ Get the medic in here.

22:28.639 --> 22:30.641
Okay, stop the clock.
Stop the clock.

22:30.641 --> 22:32.601
‐ Get the medic in here.

22:32.601 --> 22:34.436
‐ Where is it
coming from exactly?

22:34.436 --> 22:36.397
‐ Two fingers, three fingers.
‐ Right there?

22:36.397 --> 22:38.649
‐ This is the first time
in over 100 episodes

22:38.649 --> 22:40.484
we've stopped the clock.

22:40.484 --> 22:41.735
‐ The fighting spirit
in Chuck.

22:41.735 --> 22:43.404
‐ I didn't think
it was that sharp.

22:43.404 --> 22:44.488
‐ Stitches?

22:44.488 --> 22:45.614
‐ Yeah.
‐ Possible.

22:45.614 --> 22:47.283
‐ Possible?
How you feeling?

22:47.283 --> 22:49.076
‐ I'm feeling good.

22:49.076 --> 22:50.619
‐ How you feeling
about continuing?

22:50.619 --> 22:51.954
‐ Yeah, let's do it.

22:51.954 --> 22:53.497
If they want me
out of the competition,

22:53.497 --> 22:54.999
they gonna have to drag me out.

22:54.999 --> 22:56.750
<i>I'm not gonna quit.</i>
<i>I'm not gonna give up.</i>

22:56.750 --> 22:58.252
I'm gonna try to finish.

22:58.252 --> 22:59.336
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:59.336 --> 23:01.547
‐ Chuck, you good?
‐ Yes, sir.

23:01.547 --> 23:04.884
‐ All right,
so Chuck wants to finish

23:04.884 --> 23:06.844
the last six minutes
of this competition.

23:06.844 --> 23:07.970
Let's do it.

23:07.970 --> 23:09.763
All right, bladesmiths.

23:09.763 --> 23:11.473
Your time starts...

23:11.473 --> 23:12.433
now.

23:12.433 --> 23:14.602
‐ Ooh, boy.
[applause]

23:14.602 --> 23:17.229
‐ Go.
‐ Way to fight, buddy.

23:17.229 --> 23:20.065
‐ I'm gonna do whatever I can
in whatever time I have left.

23:20.065 --> 23:21.483
‐ Two minutes!

23:21.483 --> 23:26.238
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:26.238 --> 23:28.032
‐ Five, four,

23:28.032 --> 23:30.868
three, two, one.

23:30.868 --> 23:32.661
Bladesmiths, drop your tools.

23:32.661 --> 23:34.079
Stop what you're doing.

23:34.079 --> 23:36.957
This second round
of competition is over.

23:36.957 --> 23:38.167
‐ I'm gonna get you
stitched up.

23:38.167 --> 23:39.335
‐ Oh, okay.

23:39.335 --> 23:41.337
[applause]

23:41.337 --> 23:44.006
‐ Good job, Chuck.
We'll see you after.

23:44.006 --> 23:45.424
<i>‐ Definitely inspiring to see</i>

23:45.424 --> 23:46.926
<i>Chuck come back</i>
<i>from an injury like that</i>

23:46.926 --> 23:49.094
and attempt
to finish his knife,

23:49.094 --> 23:51.388
<i>but my goal is to win</i>
<i>"Forged in Fire"</i>

23:51.388 --> 23:52.765
<i>and be the champion.</i>

23:52.765 --> 23:54.850
<i>I really want to make it</i>
<i>to round three.</i>

23:54.850 --> 23:57.019
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:57.019 --> 24:00.022
‐ How you doing, Chuck?
‐ Good. Careless mistake.

24:00.022 --> 24:02.316
‐ All right, bladesmiths,
welcome to the strength test.

24:02.316 --> 24:03.734
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:03.734 --> 24:05.527
To test the strength
and durability of your blades,

24:05.527 --> 24:07.279
as well as the overall
construction of your knives,

24:07.279 --> 24:10.074
I'll be chopping them
into these steel Tonka trucks.

24:10.074 --> 24:11.492
Remember,
this test is all about

24:11.492 --> 24:12.826
what those trucks
do to your knives,

24:12.826 --> 24:14.328
not what your knives
do to the trucks.

24:14.328 --> 24:15.746
Tommy, you're up first.
You ready?

24:15.746 --> 24:16.705
‐ Let's do it.

24:16.705 --> 24:18.123
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:18.123 --> 24:20.751
<i>Round two,</i>
<i>I tried to fix the issues</i>

24:20.751 --> 24:23.629
<i>with the cracks in my blade</i>
<i>by trying to grind them out.</i>

24:23.629 --> 24:25.506
I'm just hoping
nothing breaks.

24:25.506 --> 24:32.471
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:42.022 --> 24:44.566
‐ Well, Tommy,
you've got some issues.

24:44.566 --> 24:47.403
Your blade is now actually
three pieces:

24:47.403 --> 24:49.154
the two you can see,

24:49.154 --> 24:51.573
<i>and there's a section missing</i>
<i>off the tip here as well.</i>

24:51.573 --> 24:54.243
<i>There's a dark line</i>
<i>right here on the edge,</i>

24:54.243 --> 24:57.329
which means that there was
a crack here before it broke,

24:57.329 --> 24:59.748
and that's in amongst
all of these spiderweb cracks,

24:59.748 --> 25:02.876
so obviously they haven't
all been removed,

25:02.876 --> 25:04.837
and this is the reason
that this failed.

25:04.837 --> 25:08.465
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:08.465 --> 25:10.718
‐ Tommy, your blade suffered
a catastrophic failure

25:10.718 --> 25:12.553
after four strikes
on this toy truck.

25:12.553 --> 25:15.389
However, it doesn't mean
you're out of this competition.

25:15.389 --> 25:16.765
John, you're up next.

25:16.765 --> 25:18.434
Your blade has to survive

25:18.434 --> 25:20.060
four strikes to stay
in this competition.

25:20.060 --> 25:21.687
You ready for this?
‐ Yup.

25:21.687 --> 25:23.397
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:23.397 --> 25:25.524
<i>Pretty nervous</i>
<i>about surviving four hits.</i>

25:25.524 --> 25:27.109
<i>I know I've got cracks</i>
<i>in the blade,</i>

25:27.109 --> 25:29.778
and I'm just hoping
my blade survives.

25:31.864 --> 25:34.867
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:34.867 --> 25:39.830
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:41.707 --> 25:42.750
‐ Well, John,
first things first,

25:42.750 --> 25:44.043
you're all in one piece here,

25:44.043 --> 25:46.211
but the blade took damage.

25:46.211 --> 25:47.963
<i>I mean, there is chipping.</i>

25:47.963 --> 25:50.549
But I like the fit‐up
you did here with the guard.

25:50.549 --> 25:52.718
Your knife is in one piece.
Well done.

25:52.718 --> 25:53.886
‐ Thank you.

25:53.886 --> 25:57.389
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:57.389 --> 25:58.891
‐ Well, John,
your blade held up.

25:58.891 --> 26:00.392
Good job.

26:00.392 --> 26:04.897
Chuck, there's a major problem
with your blade here.

26:04.897 --> 26:07.274
Your handle isn't affixed
to the blade.

26:07.274 --> 26:10.069
<i>No epoxy, no pins.</i>

26:10.069 --> 26:12.237
We cannot continue
testing with your blade.

26:12.237 --> 26:14.740
You bled for this one, man.

26:14.740 --> 26:16.700
And I hate to say it,
but I have to ask you

26:16.700 --> 26:17.743
to please leave The Forge.

26:17.743 --> 26:18.911
‐ Okay.

26:18.911 --> 26:21.080
[applause]

26:21.080 --> 26:22.956
<i>I feel great about</i>
<i>this overall experience.</i>

26:22.956 --> 26:24.208
<i>I've had a good time with it.</i>

26:24.208 --> 26:25.542
‐ Respect, sir.

26:25.542 --> 26:29.254
‐ Learned a few things
not to do and to do,

26:29.254 --> 26:30.422
<i>and I learned</i>
<i>that I probably shouldn't</i>

26:30.422 --> 26:32.049
<i>be handling</i>
<i>a sharp‐edged blade.</i>

26:32.049 --> 26:33.133
<i>I should've wrapped it.</i>

26:33.133 --> 26:35.511
I have seven stitches
in this finger,

26:35.511 --> 26:37.221
five in this one,
five in this one.

26:37.221 --> 26:39.473
<i>I'm hoping it's not gonna</i>
<i>slow me down too much</i>

26:39.473 --> 26:40.516
when I get back home.

26:40.516 --> 26:43.519
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

26:43.519 --> 26:44.645
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:44.645 --> 26:46.480
‐ John, Tommy, congratulations.

26:46.480 --> 26:47.773
You fellas have made it

26:47.773 --> 26:49.691
into the final round
of this competition.

26:49.691 --> 26:51.443
It's time to step
up your games

26:51.443 --> 26:54.446
and make something worthy
of a "Forged in Fire" champion.

26:54.446 --> 26:56.532
Now it's time to send you
back to your home forges

26:56.532 --> 26:59.409
to re‐create an iconic
weapon from history.

26:59.409 --> 27:00.786
That weapon is...

27:00.786 --> 27:02.996
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:02.996 --> 27:08.085
The M1832 foot artillery sword.

27:08.085 --> 27:11.964
<i>The M1832 foot artillery sword</i>
<i>is the American re‐creation</i>

27:11.964 --> 27:13.465
<i>of a French artillery sword</i>

27:13.465 --> 27:16.468
<i>modeled after the infamous</i>
<i>Roman gladius.</i>

27:16.468 --> 27:18.137
<i>Featuring a short</i>
<i>and stout blade,</i>

27:18.137 --> 27:19.638
<i>the weapon</i>
<i>has an ornate handle</i>

27:19.638 --> 27:22.140
<i>cast entirely of brass.</i>

27:22.140 --> 27:24.393
<i>Feathers or scales</i>
<i>are traditionally molded</i>

27:24.393 --> 27:26.186
<i>into the handle,</i>
<i>and an eagle is etched</i>

27:26.186 --> 27:28.480
<i>into the pommel</i>
<i>to honor America.</i>

27:28.480 --> 27:30.482
<i>Produced through the end</i>
<i>of the 19th century,</i>

27:30.482 --> 27:33.485
<i>the M1832 was issued</i>
<i>to artillerymen</i>

27:33.485 --> 27:35.320
<i>but more widely used</i>
<i>to clear paths</i>

27:35.320 --> 27:36.655
<i>through thick brush</i>

27:36.655 --> 27:39.533
<i>and as the last‐minute</i>
<i>lifesaver.</i>

27:39.533 --> 27:40.951
<i>When called upon,</i>

27:40.951 --> 27:42.661
<i>the sword was lethal</i>
<i>in close quarters</i>

27:42.661 --> 27:44.329
<i>and was employed</i>
<i>by disemboweling horses</i>

27:44.329 --> 27:45.664
<i>to bring down the rider,</i>

27:45.664 --> 27:48.500
<i>who then was finished</i>
<i>in quick fashion.</i>

27:48.500 --> 27:49.543
Make sure your blades

27:49.543 --> 27:51.044
fall within the following
parameters.

27:51.044 --> 27:54.131
The length of the blade must be
between 19 and 21 inches,

27:54.131 --> 27:56.466
be double‐edged,
and include a triple fuller

27:56.466 --> 27:57.968
on each side of the blade.

27:57.968 --> 28:00.053
In addition, you must have
a dragon scale

28:00.053 --> 28:02.556
detailed handle and a pommel.

28:02.556 --> 28:04.182
<i>‐ It's a very odd sword.</i>

28:04.182 --> 28:05.350
<i>It's long enough</i>
<i>to be a sword,</i>

28:05.350 --> 28:06.518
<i>but it's not exactly like</i>

28:06.518 --> 28:08.520
what you imagine a sword being.

28:08.520 --> 28:10.314
<i>I've done blades of this shape</i>

28:10.314 --> 28:11.899
but nothing exactly like.

28:11.899 --> 28:13.400
This is very unique.

28:13.400 --> 28:14.693
‐ You'll have four days
at your home forge

28:14.693 --> 28:16.320
in which to complete
this challenge.

28:16.320 --> 28:18.530
At the end of your four days,
you'll return to present

28:18.530 --> 28:20.365
your weapons to our panel
of expert judges,

28:20.365 --> 28:22.534
and after they've tested
the hell out of them,

28:22.534 --> 28:24.828
you guys will graduate
from child's play

28:24.828 --> 28:26.872
to full‐fledged
"Forged in Fire" champion

28:26.872 --> 28:29.166
who wins a check for $10,000.

28:29.166 --> 28:32.210
Good luck, bladesmiths.
We'll see you in four days.

28:32.210 --> 28:34.046
‐ Good luck, man.
‐ Thanks.

28:34.046 --> 28:37.090
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:37.090 --> 28:39.468
<i>‐ Excited to be</i>
<i>back at my home forge,</i>

28:39.468 --> 28:41.720
<i>and I'm ready</i>
<i>to get started on things.</i>

28:41.720 --> 28:44.556
In the first two rounds,
I made hands down

28:44.556 --> 28:46.975
the ugliest blade
that I've ever made before,

28:46.975 --> 28:48.393
<i>so I feel like I've gotta</i>
<i>really make something</i>

28:48.393 --> 28:51.772
that's gonna redeem me
in the eyes of the judges.

28:51.772 --> 28:53.899
So I'm gonna do
a Damascus blade.

28:53.899 --> 28:56.068
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:56.068 --> 28:58.403
I'm gonna set the welds
on the hydraulic press

28:58.403 --> 29:01.156
that I designed
and built from scratch.

29:01.156 --> 29:02.950
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:02.950 --> 29:04.284
<i>Start with seven layers.</i>

29:04.284 --> 29:06.578
We're gonna cut that
into three pieces

29:06.578 --> 29:09.081
after it gets forge welded.

29:09.081 --> 29:10.248
Then I'm gonna stack that.

29:10.248 --> 29:11.917
I'm gonna repeat
that process three times.

29:11.917 --> 29:14.086
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:14.086 --> 29:15.671
Then we're gonna do a twist...

29:15.671 --> 29:17.089
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:17.089 --> 29:18.590
That's gonna look pretty cool.

29:18.590 --> 29:20.425
And then hopefully
get the blade forged out.

29:20.425 --> 29:21.468
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:21.468 --> 29:22.678
That's looking good.

29:22.678 --> 29:27.307
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:27.307 --> 29:29.601
<i>‐ Back here in my shop</i>

29:29.601 --> 29:31.478
<i>here in Gainesville, Texas,</i>

29:31.478 --> 29:34.272
and I'm taking on the M1832
foot artillery sword.

29:34.272 --> 29:35.732
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:35.732 --> 29:38.777
Today I want to get
the basics forged out.

29:38.777 --> 29:40.112
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:40.112 --> 29:42.155
<i>I'm using a car leaf spring</i>

29:42.155 --> 29:43.615
<i>because I use</i>
<i>the leaf spring a lot.</i>

29:43.615 --> 29:45.117
It makes a really good blade.

29:45.117 --> 29:48.954
<i>It hardens really well,</i>
<i>and it tempers really well.</i>

29:48.954 --> 29:51.540
<i>My secret weapon</i>
<i>for moving this metal</i>

29:51.540 --> 29:53.125
is an eight‐pound hammer.

29:53.125 --> 29:54.668
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:54.668 --> 29:55.961
<i>Why?</i>

29:55.961 --> 29:58.213
Everything's bigger in Texas.
That's why.

29:58.213 --> 29:59.339
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:59.339 --> 30:00.799
My tang
was a little off‐center,

30:00.799 --> 30:02.384
so I had
to fix it.

30:02.384 --> 30:04.052
<i>I'm gonna throw it</i>
<i>in the hydraulic press</i>

30:04.052 --> 30:05.470
to get it centered out.

30:05.470 --> 30:10.308
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:10.308 --> 30:12.477
A little slower. [laughs]

30:12.477 --> 30:15.313
<i>She's a little ugly,</i>
<i>but she moves metal.</i>

30:15.313 --> 30:16.523
That's all that matters.

30:16.523 --> 30:18.900
Ah, perfect.

30:18.900 --> 30:19.985
Whoo‐hoo.

30:19.985 --> 30:21.653
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:21.653 --> 30:24.990
<i>‐ Today I'm going</i>
<i>to get working on the handle.</i>

30:24.990 --> 30:26.199
<i>I'm gonna be putting</i>
<i>a lot of my own twists</i>

30:26.199 --> 30:27.325
<i>into this weapon.</i>

30:27.325 --> 30:31.163
So I'm making
a cast bronze handle.

30:31.163 --> 30:32.622
<i>In order to cast this</i>
<i>out of the bronze,</i>

30:32.622 --> 30:34.291
<i>I've gotta make</i>
<i>a positive regardless,</i>

30:34.291 --> 30:36.084
so I could use
any type of wood.

30:36.084 --> 30:37.544
I could use clay.

30:37.544 --> 30:40.338
<i>This is just a really easy</i>
<i>material to work with.</i>

30:40.338 --> 30:44.009
So the idea is that the metal
is gonna travel down this tube

30:44.009 --> 30:45.761
and it's gonna fill
this handle up.

30:45.761 --> 30:47.512
It's gonna come down
to the bottom, fill these up,

30:47.512 --> 30:52.392
and those will come out
in the mold as cast bronze.

30:52.392 --> 30:55.896
<i>So this is a razor tip</i>
<i>wood burner.</i>

30:55.896 --> 30:58.899
<i>I'm gonna use this to put</i>
<i>the dragon scale texture.</i>

30:58.899 --> 31:01.359
<i>This handle's gonna take</i>
<i>longer than the blade</i>

31:01.359 --> 31:02.861
<i>when it's all said and done,</i>

31:02.861 --> 31:04.738
but I think it's gonna be
well worth it.

31:04.738 --> 31:07.032
Love it.
Looks great.

31:07.032 --> 31:08.700
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:08.700 --> 31:12.370
<i>‐ Yesterday I put in</i>
<i>the fullers and quenched.</i>

31:12.370 --> 31:15.040
So I'm gonna start forging
the guard and pommel.

31:15.040 --> 31:16.833
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:16.833 --> 31:18.543
Git 'er done.

31:18.543 --> 31:19.878
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:19.878 --> 31:22.923
<i>Using a piece of round stock,</i>
<i>mild steel.</i>

31:22.923 --> 31:25.383
<i>Nothing special, but it works.</i>

31:25.383 --> 31:28.053
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:28.053 --> 31:29.554
Looks good.

31:29.554 --> 31:32.641
<i>So grind the bevels in</i>
<i>is what I'm gonna do next.</i>

31:32.641 --> 31:34.226
<i>I'm here, round three.</i>

31:34.226 --> 31:36.770
<i>So happy I'm in round three</i>
<i>to begin with.</i>

31:36.770 --> 31:39.314
<i>And the build so far</i>
<i>is going really good.</i>

31:43.026 --> 31:44.194
[bleep].

31:44.194 --> 31:45.737
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:45.737 --> 31:47.906
My blade goes through,
and it catches on the belt.

31:47.906 --> 31:49.908
<i>It has happened to me</i>
<i>in a similar situation</i>

31:49.908 --> 31:51.701
where it's catastrophic.

31:51.701 --> 31:54.246
This stupid thing.

31:54.246 --> 31:58.875
I have a curl
in my actual edge.

31:58.875 --> 32:01.086
<i>I have to match</i>
<i>the rest of the edge</i>

32:01.086 --> 32:03.088
<i>to that lower point now.</i>

32:03.088 --> 32:05.590
If I don't, this could
potentially be a weak spot.

32:05.590 --> 32:06.758
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:06.758 --> 32:08.009
<i>Just gonna grind it out.</i>

32:08.009 --> 32:10.470
<i>Nothing I can do</i>
<i>other than that.</i>

32:10.470 --> 32:11.972
<i>Just gotta roll</i>
<i>with adversity.</i>

32:11.972 --> 32:15.100
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:15.100 --> 32:18.103
‐ Today I have to finish
getting the handle cast.

32:18.103 --> 32:19.813
<i>I've got the original built.</i>

32:19.813 --> 32:23.608
Now I need to make
the mold for it.

32:23.608 --> 32:26.236
So this is casting sand.

32:26.236 --> 32:28.488
It holds shape really well.

32:28.488 --> 32:30.240
<i>So what I'm gonna do</i>
<i>is pack this down</i>

32:30.240 --> 32:32.993
<i>into the bottom of my flask,</i>

32:32.993 --> 32:34.786
<i>lay my positive in there,</i>

32:34.786 --> 32:36.913
<i>and then pack it in</i>
<i>nice and tight.</i>

32:36.913 --> 32:40.125
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:40.125 --> 32:42.586
Beautiful.

32:42.586 --> 32:44.296
That's awesome.

32:44.296 --> 32:46.464
So I've got my two halves now.

32:46.464 --> 32:48.258
Now I'm ready to put them
back together

32:48.258 --> 32:49.843
<i>and get them out</i>
<i>to the foundry.</i>

32:49.843 --> 32:51.136
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:51.136 --> 32:52.762
<i>I've got some bronze</i>

32:52.762 --> 32:54.306
<i>that I'm gonna start</i>
<i>melting down.</i>

32:54.306 --> 32:56.266
<i>Once those get</i>
<i>to a molten state,</i>

32:56.266 --> 32:57.809
<i>then we'll be ready to pour.</i>

32:57.809 --> 32:59.728
The first time
you're casting any design,

32:59.728 --> 33:01.438
<i>there's always a lot of issues</i>
<i>that can come out.</i>

33:01.438 --> 33:03.648
<i>You know, the metal</i>
<i>could cool down too much</i>

33:03.648 --> 33:05.192
<i>before it gets down</i>
<i>to the bottom.</i>

33:05.192 --> 33:06.985
The mold could
collapse on itself.

33:06.985 --> 33:10.322
<i>It could just wreck inside</i>
<i>and I don't know it.</i>

33:10.322 --> 33:11.823
All right.

33:11.823 --> 33:13.617
<i>If this doesn't work,</i>
<i>I'm screwed.</i>

33:13.617 --> 33:16.328
A bad pour is gonna set me back
at least half a day.

33:16.328 --> 33:17.954
I really don't have
that time to spend.

33:17.954 --> 33:24.961
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:26.504 --> 33:28.757
Oh.

33:28.757 --> 33:30.675
Whoa.

33:30.675 --> 33:33.511
That was 3,000 degrees of metal

33:33.511 --> 33:36.181
hitting 60‐degree water.

33:36.181 --> 33:37.140
There she is.

33:37.140 --> 33:38.975
Whoo!

33:38.975 --> 33:40.685
The cool thing about bronze

33:40.685 --> 33:42.687
is that there's
no carbon in it,

33:42.687 --> 33:44.356
so you don't have to worry
about cracking

33:44.356 --> 33:45.815
or anything like that.

33:45.815 --> 33:47.651
<i>I came here to prove that</i>

33:47.651 --> 33:51.029
<i>I can deliver more than I did</i>
<i>in the first two rounds,</i>

33:51.029 --> 33:53.573
and I'm really excited to show
the judges what I've done.

33:53.573 --> 33:56.326
That's a $10,000 sword
if I've ever seen one.

33:56.326 --> 33:57.827
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:57.827 --> 34:00.372
<i>‐ Today I have to work</i>
<i>on my handle</i>

34:00.372 --> 34:01.539
and then put them together,

34:01.539 --> 34:03.333
<i>and then I'm done.</i>

34:03.333 --> 34:05.543
<i>I have a little piece</i>
<i>in the wood handle</i>

34:05.543 --> 34:07.170
<i>that's just, like,</i>
<i>stuck in there that</i>

34:07.170 --> 34:08.964
<i>I don't want</i>
<i>to keep drilling at,</i>

34:08.964 --> 34:11.549
<i>so we're gonna do</i>
<i>a burn‐in.</i>

34:11.549 --> 34:16.513
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:16.513 --> 34:17.722
Whoo!

34:17.722 --> 34:21.226
Handle is...completely fitted,
so sweet.

34:21.226 --> 34:23.228
Last thing on my checklist
is fit and finish,

34:23.228 --> 34:25.397
so let's get it done.

34:25.397 --> 34:27.899
<i>My age has definitely</i>
<i>made me the underdog</i>

34:27.899 --> 34:29.067
<i>in this competition.</i>

34:29.067 --> 34:30.402
I mean, I'm still
in high school.

34:30.402 --> 34:32.237
<i>I think John should be</i>
<i>worried a little bit.</i>

34:32.237 --> 34:35.198
I think he underestimates me,
so we're gonna have to see.

34:35.198 --> 34:37.075
It's got a little heft to it,
but I mean...

34:37.075 --> 34:38.243
you can move it around.

34:38.243 --> 34:40.036
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:40.036 --> 34:45.583
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:45.583 --> 34:47.252
‐ John, Tommy, welcome back.

34:47.252 --> 34:49.421
You boys have had four days
at your home forges

34:49.421 --> 34:51.089
to work on your finale weapons.

34:51.089 --> 34:53.300
And I must say, I don't know
that I've ever seen

34:53.300 --> 34:55.051
two weapons so different.

34:55.051 --> 34:56.261
John, how'd it go for you?

34:56.261 --> 34:57.554
<i>‐ It went great.</i>

34:57.554 --> 35:00.223
<i>I did 185 layers</i>
<i>of twist‐pattern Damascus,</i>

35:00.223 --> 35:01.891
<i>15N20 and 1080,</i>

35:01.891 --> 35:03.977
<i>and a cast bronze handle.</i>

35:03.977 --> 35:06.229
‐ All right.
Tommy, how'd it go for you?

35:06.229 --> 35:07.439
Tell the judges
about your blade.

35:07.439 --> 35:08.773
<i>‐ Went really well.</i>

35:08.773 --> 35:11.276
<i>I used a piece of car leaf</i>
<i>to make my blade.</i>

35:11.276 --> 35:13.111
<i>It's a little ugly,</i>
<i>but I think</i>

35:13.111 --> 35:14.613
<i>form over function for sure.</i>

35:14.613 --> 35:16.072
‐ All right, gentlemen.

35:16.072 --> 35:17.699
Your weapons will now
be put through a series

35:17.699 --> 35:19.159
of three tests:
a strength test,

35:19.159 --> 35:21.745
a sharpness test,
and up first, the KEAL test.

35:21.745 --> 35:22.787
Doug?

35:22.787 --> 35:25.415
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:25.415 --> 35:27.459
‐ To find out what kind
of deadly force your

35:27.459 --> 35:30.295
artillery swords can supply,
I will take your weapon,

35:30.295 --> 35:32.297
deliver killing slashes
on this ballistics dummy.

35:32.297 --> 35:34.299
John, you're up first.
You ready for this?

35:34.299 --> 35:36.217
‐ Ready.
‐ Let's do this.

35:36.217 --> 35:38.178
<i>‐ Coming into this test,</i>

35:38.178 --> 35:39.638
<i>I'm just hoping</i>
<i>that my blade holds up.</i>

35:39.638 --> 35:42.515
I know it's a sharp blade,
but I hope that it KEALs.

35:42.515 --> 35:49.522
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:07.624 --> 36:10.001
‐ All right, John,
first up, I like the beauty

36:10.001 --> 36:12.379
of an all‐metal construction,
and the Damascus pattern

36:12.379 --> 36:14.172
you have here is gorgeous.

36:14.172 --> 36:15.507
The weight is all the way
in the handle,

36:15.507 --> 36:17.217
allows for good recovery

36:17.217 --> 36:19.427
and forward delivery
of strikes.

36:19.427 --> 36:22.347
Your edges are very sharp.

36:22.347 --> 36:23.390
Every cut cuts deep,

36:23.390 --> 36:25.350
cuts the bone,
and into the organs.

36:25.350 --> 36:28.520
And most importantly, sir,
it will KEAL.

36:28.520 --> 36:29.688
‐ Thank you.

36:29.688 --> 36:31.231
‐ All right, Tommy, your turn.
You ready?

36:31.231 --> 36:33.024
‐ Git 'er done.

36:33.024 --> 36:36.194
<i>I know my blade is sharp.</i>
<i>I think it's gonna KEAL.</i>

36:36.194 --> 36:37.654
Plain and simple,
it's gonna be deadly.

36:37.654 --> 36:44.661
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:49.999 --> 36:53.002
‐ [grunting]

36:53.002 --> 36:59.968
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:59.968 --> 37:02.137
All right, Tommy, let's talk
about your weapon here.

37:02.137 --> 37:03.388
It is a beast.

37:03.388 --> 37:06.182
The weight of your weapon
is all forward,

37:06.182 --> 37:07.892
that it actually takes a lot

37:07.892 --> 37:10.061
to pull it away
for a second strike.

37:10.061 --> 37:11.563
But the thing
that your beast does have

37:11.563 --> 37:13.606
is a very sharp edge.

37:13.606 --> 37:16.234
Every cut is very deep,

37:16.234 --> 37:18.528
but it takes a lot of work
to control this beast.

37:18.528 --> 37:21.448
More importantly, though, sir,
it will KEAL.

37:21.448 --> 37:24.909
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:24.909 --> 37:26.911
‐ All right, gentlemen, it's
time for the strength test.

37:26.911 --> 37:28.913
Now, why bring swords
to a gun range?

37:28.913 --> 37:31.416
Well, so you two can join
one of our two clubs,

37:31.416 --> 37:34.586
the "Oh, my God, they broke
my blade with a bullet" club

37:34.586 --> 37:36.838
or the bulletproof‐sword club.

37:36.838 --> 37:37.922
So to test your blades,

37:37.922 --> 37:39.549
we've got our firearm
locked in a vise.

37:39.549 --> 37:41.968
We've got your blade locked
in another vise downrange.

37:41.968 --> 37:43.803
Gonna fire one round
at that thing.

37:43.803 --> 37:45.805
It should split
that bullet clean

37:45.805 --> 37:48.016
or, worst of all,
see that blade shatter.

37:48.016 --> 37:49.893
John, you're up first.
You ready for this?

37:49.893 --> 37:51.102
‐ Yup.
‐ Okay.

37:51.102 --> 37:54.105
‐ I'm really nervous.

37:54.105 --> 37:56.107
‐ This bullet could just
split my blade in half.

37:56.107 --> 37:58.443
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

37:58.443 --> 37:59.444
‐ Fire.

37:59.444 --> 38:00.695
[gunshot]

38:00.695 --> 38:02.489
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:02.489 --> 38:03.948
‐ Four holes.

38:03.948 --> 38:05.617
[gunshot]

38:05.617 --> 38:09.662
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:12.332 --> 38:13.625
‐ [laughs]

38:13.625 --> 38:15.960
I thought I felt that
you lost a hair of edge.

38:15.960 --> 38:17.962
That's bullet
hung up on the blade.

38:17.962 --> 38:19.130
‐ Awesome.

38:19.130 --> 38:21.090
‐ You can actually see
top and bottom

38:21.090 --> 38:23.384
where that bullet
went across your blade.

38:23.384 --> 38:25.178
Now, you can see there's four
holes in the thing over there.

38:25.178 --> 38:27.013
That's the lead core
in the jacket going

38:27.013 --> 38:28.348
in different directions,

38:28.348 --> 38:29.974
so you split that bullet
nicely.

38:29.974 --> 38:32.310
I don't see any damage
to your blade.

38:32.310 --> 38:33.311
Well done.
‐ Excellent.

38:33.311 --> 38:34.896
‐ Good job.
‐ Thank you.

38:34.896 --> 38:36.314
‐ All right, Tommy,
you ready for this?

38:36.314 --> 38:38.483
‐ Let's do it.

38:38.483 --> 38:40.443
<i>My blade is stouter,</i>
<i>it's bigger, and it's badder.</i>

38:40.443 --> 38:42.320
<i>I expect it to stand up</i>
<i>to this bullet.</i>

38:42.320 --> 38:45.156
Shoot it.

38:45.156 --> 38:46.157
‐ Fire.

38:46.157 --> 38:48.201
[gunshot]

38:48.201 --> 38:49.494
‐ There we go.

38:49.494 --> 38:50.912
[gunshot]

38:50.912 --> 38:54.541
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:55.375 --> 38:57.168
‐ All right, Tommy,
well, your blade

38:57.168 --> 38:58.920
took some damage
in that bullet test.

38:58.920 --> 39:00.338
There's a chip in one spot.

39:00.338 --> 39:02.590
And the other spot,
you can actually

39:02.590 --> 39:04.509
hear my fingernail catching
on that roll.

39:04.509 --> 39:07.679
Having said that,
it doesn't feel bad in my hand,

39:07.679 --> 39:10.014
but it is very heavy
for this type of sword.

39:10.014 --> 39:11.724
But as far as
the strength test goes,

39:11.724 --> 39:14.018
as you can clearly see,
you took some damage.

39:14.018 --> 39:17.188
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:17.188 --> 39:18.690
‐ All right, bladesmiths,

39:18.690 --> 39:20.525
now that we know your blades
can take a bullet,

39:20.525 --> 39:22.193
it's time to find out
if they can cut.

39:22.193 --> 39:26.531
This is the sharpness test,
the shot bag slice.

39:26.531 --> 39:28.867
Now, unlike the strength test,
this is all about

39:28.867 --> 39:31.703
what the edge of your blade
will do to these shot bags.

39:31.703 --> 39:34.163
A sharp blade
should cut cleanly.

39:34.163 --> 39:35.456
John, you're up first.
You ready for this?

39:35.456 --> 39:37.500
‐ Yup.
‐ Let's do this.

39:39.043 --> 39:46.009
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:53.057 --> 39:54.934
‐ Good job, man.
‐ [chuckles]

39:54.934 --> 39:57.395
‐ This is what I love
about your blade, the balance.

39:57.395 --> 40:00.398
It is fun to wield.
It is fun to move around.

40:00.398 --> 40:02.567
It cuts with every slice.

40:02.567 --> 40:03.943
It will cut.

40:03.943 --> 40:05.361
‐ Thank you.

40:05.361 --> 40:06.404
‐ All right, Tommy,
it's your turn, sir.

40:06.404 --> 40:08.448
You ready?
‐ Let's do it.

40:08.448 --> 40:09.991
<i>I feel like</i>
<i>I'm a little behind.</i>

40:09.991 --> 40:12.410
<i>I took some damage</i>
<i>in the last test,</i>

40:12.410 --> 40:14.913
and I really need to outperform
now in order to win.

40:14.913 --> 40:21.961
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:28.593 --> 40:30.345
‐ Awesome.

40:30.345 --> 40:32.221
‐ All right, Tommy,
on the stationary cuts,

40:32.221 --> 40:33.264
it cuts cleanly.

40:33.264 --> 40:34.599
It's a sharp blade.

40:34.599 --> 40:37.268
Now, when I'm moving around
and changing my balance,

40:37.268 --> 40:38.937
because of the weight
of the blade,

40:38.937 --> 40:40.605
it does affect
the way I'm cutting,

40:40.605 --> 40:42.774
so some of the cuts are not
clean all the way through.

40:42.774 --> 40:44.025
There are some strands.

40:44.025 --> 40:45.443
More importantly,
your weapon here,

40:45.443 --> 40:47.946
though a beast,
it will cut.

40:47.946 --> 40:50.114
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:50.114 --> 40:52.992
‐ John, Tommy, the judges
have made their final decision.

40:52.992 --> 40:55.286
Our new "Forged in Fire"
champion is...

40:55.286 --> 40:58.623
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:58.623 --> 40:59.958
John, congratulations.

40:59.958 --> 41:01.793
You're the "Forged in Fire"
champion.

41:01.793 --> 41:05.129
Tommy, unfortunately,
your blade didn't make the cut.

41:05.129 --> 41:06.965
‐ Tommy, this came down
to three things:

41:06.965 --> 41:09.550
the weight of your blade
made it harder to wield,

41:09.550 --> 41:10.969
its rough construction,

41:10.969 --> 41:12.971
and the fact that it took
damage in the strength test.

41:12.971 --> 41:14.472
Those are the reasons
we're letting you go.

41:14.472 --> 41:16.349
<i>♪ ♪</i>

41:16.349 --> 41:19.852
‐ Tommy, you made a beast, but
today it didn't make the cut.

41:19.852 --> 41:20.895
Please leave the range.

41:20.895 --> 41:22.313
<i>♪ ♪</i>

41:22.313 --> 41:24.107
‐ Thank you, sir.
‐ Thank you.

41:24.107 --> 41:25.483
<i>‐ I completely agree</i>
<i>with the outcome.</i>

41:25.483 --> 41:27.068
<i>John made a better sword.</i>

41:27.068 --> 41:29.487
Beauty overcame the beast
in this situation,

41:29.487 --> 41:31.531
<i>and he deserves it.</i>

41:31.531 --> 41:34.409
Congrats, buddy.
‐ Good job, man. See ya.

41:34.409 --> 41:35.660
‐ From here, it's just about
getting better

41:35.660 --> 41:36.995
and refining my skills.

41:36.995 --> 41:39.080
<i>I may not be</i>
<i>a "Forged in Fire" champion,</i>

41:39.080 --> 41:41.249
but I'm damn sure proud
of how far I came.

41:41.249 --> 41:44.502
<i>♪ ♪</i>

41:44.502 --> 41:46.004
‐ John, congratulations.

41:46.004 --> 41:48.172
You are the "Forged in Fire"
champion,

41:48.172 --> 41:51.050
and that is a title that
comes with a check for $10,000.

41:51.050 --> 41:52.885
Good job, brother.
‐ Thank you.

41:52.885 --> 41:54.762
<i>Feels great to be the next</i>
<i>"Forged in Fire" champion.</i>

41:54.762 --> 41:56.014
‐ Good job, man.

41:56.014 --> 41:57.807
‐ I'm super proud of all
the work that I've done.

41:57.807 --> 42:02.145
I've come here and done tests
that I never would've expected,

42:02.145 --> 42:05.523
put myself into challenges that
I never would've tried before,

42:05.523 --> 42:08.693
and I've succeeded,
so I feel awesome.

42:08.693 --> 42:13.364
<i>♪ ♪</i>
